Where Education Becomes a Uniquely Woodland Experience 



Woodland School will remain closed as directed by the Governor of Michigan.
As one of the first charter schools in the state, Woodland School serves as a vibrant example of a healthy learning community.
Nestled within 250 acres of wooded land, our K-8 program provides a curriculum that is aligned with state standards but delivered in a way that promotes real life connections, student engagement, and a deep love of learning. 

 Learn More 


Join the Woodland Staff
We are seeking teacher(s) for the 2020/2021 school year. The current opening(s) are for teachers with current endorsements from the State of Michigan in one or more of the following areas; Language Arts, Social Studies, Math, Choir and or Theater. New hires must creatively meet the diverse needs of a multi-grade classroom, while providing unique curriculum.
Salary is dependent upon experience and advanced degrees. Full-time position benefits include health insurance and a 401K contribution from the school. Interested? Send a letter of interest and your resume to Woodland School Director, Jeremiah Stieve.
jstieve@woodlandschooltc.org
Application Deadline: Tuesday, May 10, 2020
Join the Woodland School Board
If you are interested in serving on the Woodland School Board, please visit the office for more information and application materials. Serving on the Board is a rewarding way to contribute to Woodland School. To view Woodland School transparency or School Board Information click here.
Watching the Forest at Woodland School
When an oak wilt infestation led to clear cutting acres of trees on the forested campus of the Woodland School, teachers Lesley Goodrick-Scanlon and Ned Milne recognized the proverbial teachable moment. Teachers and students could learn how to steward forests together.
To help design a project that would engage the whole school, the teachers turned to the Grand Traverse Stewardship Initiative (GTSI) for guidance and assistance. GTSI provided teacher support, planning assistance, some funding and helped to engage appropriate experts. GTSI Director, Chelsea Nester helped to organize a school-wide professional development program focusing on the new 20-year forest management plan developed for the Woodland School’s 250 acre campus.
Watch the short video below to learn more and become inspired.








